Contents
1. Executive Summary
This document describes an automation system that generates, reviews, and submits data-backfill code for every DAO in our service — using Gemini CLI in headless mode as the code-generation engine and a shell script as the orchestrator. The system replaces what would otherwise be repetitive, error-prone, multi-week manual work across many DAOs with a single, reproducible pipeline.
For each DAO in a CSV input list, the pipeline creates a clean workspace, prompts Gemini to write the backfill code that copies data from Cloud Spanner into Infra Spanner, runs presubmit checks, asks Gemini to self-review the output, and finally creates a changelist (CL) that is sent for human review. All of this happens unattended.
Why this matters Backfill code is highly repetitive across DAOs but small mistakes have large consequences (data loss, drift, reprocessing cost). AI generation gives us velocity; AI self-review and presubmit gates give us safety. The human reviewer spends time on judgment, not boilerplate.
2. Problem Statement
The migration from Cloud Spanner to Infra Spanner requires backfilling historical data for every DAO. Doing this manually has three problems:
Volume — there are many DAOs, each requiring its own backfill code that follows the same template but with DAO-specific schemas, key types, and transforms.
Repetition — the structure of backfill code is nearly identical across DAOs, which makes manual authoring tedious and a poor use of engineer time.
Risk of inconsistency — when many engineers (or even one engineer over many days) write similar code by hand, drift creeps in: error handling, batch sizing, retry semantics, logging conventions.
We needed a way to keep the human in the loop for review and judgment, while taking the rote authoring work off their plate.
3. Solution Overview
The solution is a shell-driven pipeline that loops over a CSV list of DAO names. For each DAO, it executes a fixed sequence of steps, calling Gemini CLI in headless mode wherever code generation or code review is required.
