3.2 Pipeline stages
#	Stage	What happens	Driver
1	Create workspace	Per-DAO clean checkout/sync so changes are isolated.	Shell
2	Generate backfill code	Gemini CLI is invoked with a prompt describing the DAO, the source/destination schemas, and the backfill template. It writes the code, tests, and config.	Gemini CLI
3	Presubmit checks	Build, lint, unit tests, formatters. Anything that fails halts the run for this DAO.	Shell
4	AI code review	A second Gemini call performs a structured review of its own output (style, correctness, edge cases) and applies fixes.	Gemini CLI
5	Validate output	Sanity-check the diff: scope is bounded, no unintended files touched, tests still pass after AI fixes.	Shell
6	Create CL	Auto-author the changelist with description, test plan, and links.	Shell
7	Send for review	Mail the CL to the appropriate reviewers (DAO owners).	Shell
8	Log status	Per-DAO success/failure recorded for the engineer to triage.	Shell
4. Why Gemini CLI in Headless Mode
Headless mode is the key enabler. It lets us call Gemini from a shell loop without any interactive terminal, which means:
The pipeline is fully unattended — start it, walk away, return to a list of CLs.
Every step is reproducible — the prompt and inputs are version-controlled, so the same DAO produces the same shape of output.
It composes — generation and review are just two more shell commands, not a separate UI workflow.
It scales linearly — adding a DAO means adding one row to the CSV; no extra engineering effort.
5. Components
5.1 Input — DAO list (CSV)
A simple CSV with one row per DAO is the only input. The orchestrator reads it line by line and dispatches each DAO into the pipeline. The CSV is the single source of truth for "what is in scope today" — adding or removing a DAO is a one-line change.
5.2 Orchestrator — shell script
The shell script is intentionally thin. Its job is sequencing, not intelligence: set up the workspace, call Gemini, run presubmit, call Gemini for review, create the CL, mail it, log the result. Each stage is a separate command that can be re-run independently if needed, which makes debugging a single failed DAO easy.
5.3 Code generation — Gemini CLI
The generation step uses a curated prompt that includes the DAO name, schema details for source and destination, and a reference example. Gemini produces the backfill code, the unit tests, and any configuration entries the build system needs. Because the prompt is the same across DAOs, output is consistent in style and structure.
5.4 AI code review
After presubmit passes, a second Gemini invocation reviews the generated code with a different prompt focused on review concerns: idiomatic patterns, edge cases, batch-size sanity, error handling, log statements. Findings are applied automatically, then presubmit is re-run.
5.5 Changelist creation
The CL description, test plan, and reviewer list are templated — the script fills in the DAO-specific details and submits the CL for human review. Reviewers see a uniform, well-described CL every time, which speeds up review.
6. Benefits and Advantages
6.1 Velocity
Hand-writing backfill code for each DAO would take a meaningful fraction of an engineer-day per DAO, multiplied across the full DAO list. The pipeline collapses that into a near-zero marginal cost per DAO: the human cost is one CL review, not one CL authoring + one CL review.
6.2 Consistency
Every CL produced by the pipeline follows the same structure, logging conventions, error handling, and test layout. Reviewers can rely on muscle memory; on-call engineers can rely on every backfill behaving the same way at runtime. There is no accidental drift between the first DAO migrated and the last.
6.3 Quality gates
The pipeline enforces multiple safety nets before any human sees the CL:
Build must pass.
Lint and formatters must pass.
Unit tests must pass.
AI self-review must complete with no open issues.
Diff must be bounded — only expected files touched.
A failure at any gate halts that DAO and surfaces a clean error log; no half-baked CLs reach the reviewer.
6.4 Reviewer leverage
Because output is uniform, reviewers can scan a CL in a fraction of the time it would take to review hand-written code. Their attention shifts from style and boilerplate to the things that actually need human judgment: schema correctness, blast radius, rollout plan.
6.5 Reproducibility and auditability
Every CL is traceable to a specific prompt and a specific input row. If a pattern needs to be updated globally — for example, a new logging requirement — we update the prompt, re-run the pipeline, and the change propagates uniformly. The log of per-DAO status gives a clear audit trail of what was generated and when.
6.6 Cost and team focus
Engineering time saved on rote authoring is redirected to the parts of the migration that actually require human judgment — schema design, rollout sequencing, incident response. The team ships faster without taking on more risk.
7. Quality and Safety Controls
Risk	Mitigation
AI generates incorrect logic	Presubmit + AI self-review + human CL review form a three-layer gate before any code lands.
Generated diff too broad	Diff sanity check halts the run if files outside the expected set are touched.
Inconsistent output across DAOs	Single curated prompt + version-controlled template ensures uniform structure.
Silent failures during a long run	Per-DAO status log makes any failure visible; no DAO is silently skipped.
Schema drift between source and destination	Prompt embeds both schemas; generated tests assert mapping correctness.
Human review fatigue	Uniform CLs mean reviewers can focus on logic, not formatting — fatigue is reduced.
8. Operating Model
8.1 How a typical run looks
Engineer updates the CSV with the DAOs in scope.
Engineer kicks off the pipeline.
Pipeline runs unattended; logs stream to a known location.
Engineer returns to a status report and a list of mailed CLs.
Engineer triages any per-DAO failures (re-run that one DAO, or hand-fix).
Reviewers approve CLs; engineer submits.
8.2 What happens on failure
Failures are scoped per DAO. One DAO failing does not block the others. The orchestrator records the failure stage (generation, presubmit, review, CL creation) and surfaces enough context to re-run the affected DAO in isolation. Most generation failures are fixed by re-prompting; most presubmit failures are fixed by the AI review step picking up missing imports or test fixtures.
9. Outcomes and Showcase
This system demonstrates several things worth highlighting:
Practical, production use of an AI agent (Gemini CLI) inside a real engineering workflow — not a demo, not a sidecar tool, but the actual mechanism that produced the merged code.
A clean separation of concerns: AI does the writing and reviewing; deterministic shell does the orchestration; humans do the judgment calls.
A reusable template — the same shape of pipeline (CSV → loop → workspace → AI generate → presubmit → AI review → CL) is directly applicable to the dual-write phase that follows, and to future similar migrations.
Measurable engineering leverage: each CL costs the engineer a review, not an authoring session.
10. Related Work and Next Steps
Backfill is phase one. Two related automation systems extend the pattern:
Dual-write automation — same pipeline shape, different prompt; modifies each DAO to write to both Cloud Spanner and Infra Spanner. Documented separately.
API verification automation — once the dual-write CLs are submitted, an AI-driven workflow exercises every write RPC end-to-end via stubby, troubleshoots failures, and produces a verification document. Documented separately.
Together these three workstreams cover the full migration arc: data is copied (backfill), new writes go to both stores (dual write), and the result is verified end-to-end (API verification).
